  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1239168154" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1239168154" />
    <a title="Tony" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/33771-tony"><img alt="Tony" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1292869016p2/33771.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1239168154?book_show_action=true">Jan 30, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tony" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tony" href="/user/show/33771-tony">Tony</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781847675712" href="/book/show/7849308-pereira-maintains">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/33771-tony?shelf=italian">italian</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/33771-tony?shelf=portugese">portugese</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1239168154" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18336426852202270877">This is a delightfully nuanced book with, I maintain, a nuanced title.<br/><br/>The quick particulars are that Pererira, a widower, is the culture editor for a Lisbon newspaper in 1938. Trouble is brewing, mostly elsewhere, but Portugal is leaning the wrong way. No matter for the apolitical Pereira who is more concerned for his deteriorating health, his heart taxed from overeating. Into his life come a young man and woman, radicals. Will Pereira help?<br/><br/>Given Pereira’s occupation, the story has more than its</span>
  <span id="freeText18336426852202270877" style="display:none">This is a delightfully nuanced book with, I maintain, a nuanced title.<br /><br />The quick particulars are that Pererira, a widower, is the culture editor for a Lisbon newspaper in 1938. Trouble is brewing, mostly elsewhere, but Portugal is leaning the wrong way. No matter for the apolitical Pereira who is more concerned for his deteriorating health, his heart taxed from overeating. Into his life come a young man and woman, radicals. Will Pereira help?<br /><br />Given Pereira’s occupation, the story has more than its share of literary references. You only need to know one though. He meets a woman on a train, and she is reading a novel by Thomas Mann, in German. They share a pleasant lunch and Pereira learns that she is Jewish and that she is fleeing. Pereira laments with her. And she tells him <i>do something</i>.<br /><br />Experienced readers will not be shocked to learn Pereira first goes to a clinic for his health, a kind of sanitarium. <i>It was perched high on the rocks.</i> And there was magic there; his health improves and he receives some guidance from the director of the clinic. Some nuanced guidance, I maintain.<br /><br />Pereira seeks answers, too, from a framed picture of his deceased wife. But that’s just a photograph, the unchanging faraway look. I maintain that Pereira always had the answer.<br /><br />I said, to start, that even the title of this novel was nuanced. It was published first in Italian as <i>Sostiene Pereira</i>. That has been variously translated as <i>Pereira Declares</i> and <i>Pereira Maintains</i>. They are both technically correct but I think there is a definite difference. To <i>declare</i> is to state absolutely and, frankly, regardless of belief. To <i>maintain</i> is to state a personal view. Let me give an example having nothing to do with this book.<br /><br />I might <i>declare</i>: Donald Trump is a dangerous fool. But if I <i>maintain</i> that view, I would say: I believe Donald Trump is a dangerous fool. The latter allows that there might be other views, and not necessarily incorrect ones. I believe I’m right.<br /><br /><i>Maintain</i> also means: to continue, to keep, to sustain, to support, to bear. Like a car, or some more human chassis, or a movement.<br /><br />With that lesson in pedantry out of the way, let me declare that Pereira <i>maintains</i>. <br /><br />I think I’ll have an omelet. And maybe some Port. I maintain.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="18336426852202270877" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


