    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_956538648" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/956538648" />
    <a title="Ian" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/31384949-ian"><img alt="Ian" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1632951275p2/31384949.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/956538648?book_show_action=true">Jun 03, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ian" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ian" href="/user/show/31384949-ian">Ian</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Unknown Binding 9781860460692" href="/book/show/1040136.Declares_Pereira">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31384949-ian?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31384949-ian?shelf=4-star-lit-fiction">4-star-lit-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31384949-ian?shelf=portugal">portugal</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer956538648" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16756513129729287677">A re-read of a book I originally read when the English translation was first published in the 1990s. I’m not sure why GR has the blurb for this edition in Spanish, but the edition with this cover and title was the one I read. The book has been published in English with at least three different titles, and originally in Italian as “Sostiene Pereira”.<br/><br/>Sometimes I’ll read a book and a few months later I’ll hardly be able to recall a single detail of it. Although I read “Declares Pereira” 20 years ag</span>
  <span id="freeText16756513129729287677" style="display:none">A re-read of a book I originally read when the English translation was first published in the 1990s. I’m not sure why GR has the blurb for this edition in Spanish, but the edition with this cover and title was the one I read. The book has been published in English with at least three different titles, and originally in Italian as “Sostiene Pereira”.<br /><br />Sometimes I’ll read a book and a few months later I’ll hardly be able to recall a single detail of it. Although I read “Declares Pereira” 20 years ago I remembered it very well before my re-read, which to me is a sign of a very effective novel. I decided to read it again after seeing the recent review by my GR Friend Abubakar Mehdi, which I recommend, and which can be found at:<br /><br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2919939020?book_show_action=false&amp;from_review_page=3">https://www.goodreads.com/review/show...</a> <br /><br />As indicated in the summary, the setting is Portugal in 1938 during the dictatorship* of Antonio Salazar. Pereira is a middle aged, seriously overweight, and extremely lonely widower who works as the culture editor of a second-rate newspaper. He is obsessed with memories of the past, and with philosophies of death and resurrection. He’s also a man of many regrets, the greatest of which is that he never had children. His only remaining interest is literature, until he meets a young man, Monteiro Rossi, and his beautiful girlfriend Marta. To Pereira, Monteiro Rossi seems like the son he never had, and on their first encounter Marta suggests to Pereira that they dance a waltz. Pereira dances the waltz “in a state of rapture”, as if he has been transported back to his lost youth.<br /><br />Monteiro Rossi and Marta are involved in left wing politics, a dangerous activity in 1930s Portugal, and despite his misgivings Pereira gets drawn into their world. On their first meeting he tells them he is apolitical except that he dislikes extremism. Pereira wants to ignore politics and immerse himself in the world of literature. The author poses the question whether it’s possible to maintain such an attitude in a society where political repression is the norm, or whether everyone needs to make their choice, to as it were, “declare” their position.<br /><br />At the time of writing this book has over 12,000 ratings and nearly 1000 reviews, so it’s quite well known. If you haven’t read it but are interested in the themes, then I would certainly recommend it.<br /><br /><br /><br />*Political scientists disagree on whether Salazar should be termed a fascist. Some argue that he is more accurately described as an authoritarian nationalist with a traditionalist/Catholic world view. Orwell made the same argument about Franco, commenting that the Spanish dictator was “more of a feudalist than a fascist”. The arguments are all available on the web if anyone wants to read them. I daresay the semantics were unimportant to those who languished in the dictators’ prisons.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="16756513129729287677" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


