    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1359616902" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1359616902" />
    <a title="Ben Winch" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5647943-ben-winch"><img alt="Ben Winch" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1605154548p2/5647943.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1359616902?book_show_action=true">Aug 09, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ben Winch" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ben Winch" href="/user/show/5647943-ben-winch">Ben Winch</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Unknown Binding 9781860460692" href="/book/show/1040136.Declares_Pereira">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5647943-ben-winch?shelf=5-stars">5-stars</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5647943-ben-winch?shelf=mainland-european">mainland-european</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5647943-ben-winch?shelf=italian">italian</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1359616902" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2346253613537547670">My third reading (at least) and, like all Tabucchi’s best work (<i><a href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/177686521' rel='nofollow noopener'>Requiem</a>, <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/381364377' rel='nofollow noopener'>Vanishing Point</a>, <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/118437.Indian_Nocturne' rel='nofollow noopener'>Indian Nocturne</a></i>), it gets better each time. In fact, I find it hard to imagine how any serious reader (who enjoys breaks from formula and doesn’t need things cut and dried) could dislike it. It’s warm, funny, charming, deft as hell. A civilised story of civilisation in danger. And an act of magic in ways I can’t describe, not without giving it away a little at least. <br/><br/>A friend (<a href='https://www.goodreads.com/user/show/11602286-stephen-p' rel='nofollow noopener'>Stephen P</a>) remarks Tabucchi’s </span>
  <span id="freeText2346253613537547670" style="display:none">My third reading (at least) and, like all Tabucchi’s best work (<i><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/177686521" rel="nofollow noopener">Requiem</a>, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/381364377" rel="nofollow noopener">Vanishing Point</a>, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/118437.Indian_Nocturne" rel="nofollow noopener">Indian Nocturne</a></i>), it gets better each time. In fact, I find it hard to imagine how any serious reader (who enjoys breaks from formula and doesn’t need things cut and dried) could dislike it. It’s warm, funny, charming, deft as hell. A civilised story of civilisation in danger. And an act of magic in ways I can’t describe, not without giving it away a little at least. <br /><br />A friend (<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/show/11602286-stephen-p" rel="nofollow noopener">Stephen P</a>) remarks Tabucchi’s strange take on death, and I’ll admit it’s something I’d never given much thought to, though it’s so in evidence here I find that hard to credit now. A sense of haunting, the quicksand pull of the past. The feeling that Tabucchi, for all his restraint, may himself be <i>gutted</i> by grief – that he knows grief intimately, if nothing else; that his characters are the visible parts of icebergs with his invisible grief below – yet his art lies in denying his own catharsis-via-his-work, or in (who knows?) blurting, catharting, <i>then</i> denying; trimming always trimming, weaving the remaining strands till what remains is purest magic, suggestive, hypnotic, lighter than air, yet never trivial, wedded to love and death and deep feeling. Tabucchi’s work – there’s no better word for it – is <i>refined</i>, but with none of the bloodlessness that implies. The blood is there if you care to see it. If you don’t you can, of course, avert your eyes. The magic of <i>Pereira</i> lies (that old cliché) as much in what is not said as in what is shown. Who is he “declaring” (or “maintaining”) to anyway? Through the masterful use of frame Tabucchi reconfigures his small tragedy as a soul’s ascendance to freedom, saying everything he (an Italian in Berlusconi’s Italy of the nineties) has to say about repressive regimes, showing clearly both the inexorable slide to police state and the bourgeois’s wilful ignorance of the process, but never with less than the highest regard for his characters, never po-facedly, always with love. All of which makes <i>Pereira</i> twice as potent as your angry dissident text. How did you feel after <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/302177397" rel="nofollow noopener">
  <i>Comrade Tulayev</i>
</a>, after <i>1984</i>? Angry? Helpless? And after <i>Pereira</i>? Scared, for sure. (The part where we learn, secondhand via a waiter whose friend gets BBC Radio, that Portugal is a dictatorship, chills me to my bones.) But overall, inspired. And by the time Pereira’s soul takes flight, for all that the “happy ending” might be a matter of perspective, elated. <br /><br />For me, the novellas of Antonio Tabucchi – <i>Pereira Declares, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/177686521" rel="nofollow noopener">Requiem</a>, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/381364377" rel="nofollow noopener">Vanishing Point</a>, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/118437.Indian_Nocturne" rel="nofollow noopener">Indian Nocturne</a></i> – are among the great works of literature of the twentieth century. But <i>quietly</i> they take their places at that table, not pushing or shoving, not declaiming their innovation or gravity, and smiling with that faraway look of past unfathomable loss as they address the assembled. Prick up your ears! It’s just possible they’ll transform your idea of what’s possible.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2346253613537547670" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


