  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3676279117" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3676279117" />
    <a title="J.C." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/52123967-j-c"><img alt="J.C." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1610295104p2/52123967.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3676279117?book_show_action=true">Dec 03, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="J.C." class="user" itemprop="url" name="J.C." href="/user/show/52123967-j-c">J.C.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781847675712" href="/book/show/7849308-pereira-maintains">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/52123967-j-c?shelf=european">european</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3676279117" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12311507323714840624">I didn&apos;t know Pereira until now. I take it he featured in crime novels before becoming back-street and overweight, while he writes his &apos;Culture&apos; page for his nervous newspaper in a broiling 1938 Lisbon. After reading his story here I wondered what might be next for Pereira, and the ending leaves plenty of leeway, which I like. <br/>Thanks to reviews from <a href='https://www.goodreads.com' rel='nofollow noopener'>Ian</a>, <a href='https://www.goodreads.com' rel='nofollow noopener'>Vlad</a> and <a href='https://www.goodreads.com' rel='nofollow noopener'>Abubakar</a>, I had understood, before reading this, that a lot rested on the repetition of &quot;Pereira maintains&quot; throughout the story (or &quot;</span>
  <span id="freeText12311507323714840624" style="display:none">I didn't know Pereira until now. I take it he featured in crime novels before becoming back-street and overweight, while he writes his 'Culture' page for his nervous newspaper in a broiling 1938 Lisbon. After reading his story here I wondered what might be next for Pereira, and the ending leaves plenty of leeway, which I like. <br />Thanks to reviews from <a href="https://www.goodreads.com" rel="nofollow noopener">Ian</a>, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com" rel="nofollow noopener">Vlad</a> and <a href="https://www.goodreads.com" rel="nofollow noopener">Abubakar</a>, I had understood, before reading this, that a lot rested on the repetition of "Pereira maintains" throughout the story (or "declares" in Ian's version) and this book is wholly about Pereira coming gradually to declare his position in a country becoming more and more Fascist, and being able to maintain his integrity in his political beliefs. Another aspect of it for me was, that the repetition of “Pereira maintains” led me to expect that there existed, somewhere in a white-washed police interrogation room, an omnipotent narrator who was writing an account, almost a kind of 'sleekit' defence of Pereira's actions, for some future student of these times. The end was different from this picture I had, and better.<br />The tone of the narrative has a similar effect to Pereira translating 19th century French authors for his culture page; it gets the message across covertly – until, that is, Pereira becomes more overt by publishing a translation of Daudet’s <i>La Dernière Classe</i>, which is anti-German, anti-fascist, and which moves him, and the story, quite definitely forward. <br />Whenever I read a story of heroism against the odds and in the face of such brutality I am in awe. This book is a marvel of understatement when it comes to heroism; for me, when the culminating moment of action takes place, it's as if that great yellow sun that makes Pereira break out in a sweat is about to frazzle mean souls of fascists everywhere. <br />And that word, "soul". Pereira, like a hero in Graham Greene, agonises over Roman Catholic doctrine of the soul (and there is Greene’s priest, too, in the background); but the word changes with its context, to become "heart" with the young idealists, Monteiro Rossi and Marta, and “ego” with the doctor – at some point there is also “personality”. As Abubakar has said (and as I have come across in a recent re-reading of <i>Dr Zhivago</i>, if the soul withers, the body withers too. Pereira’s heart problems, like Zhivago’s, are symptomatic; they are also symbolic of his dis-ease politically and morally. Even his sweating under the sun might be seen as symbolic of a suppressed fear. His engagement with the political ideals of the Monteiro Rossi and Marta seems almost involuntary, step by step, but it is clear that he must do this, or die the death that pre-occupies him, his past like a ‘sediment’ within him, to quote <a href="https://www.goodreads.com" rel="nofollow noopener">Théodore</a> in his recent review of the poems of Yehuda Amichai. <br />Pereira has taken refuge, in his quiet labours, his memories of his wife, and his omelettes and lemonade. In this refuge he is trapped. He won’t find life, and meaning, again until he has risked his safety, and asserted his inner force, his “ruling ego”. When he does, it is as if his life has found some kind of vindication. In that he is an existentialist hero. <br />Pereira, the "unassuming" hero, as <a href="https://www.goodreads.com" rel="nofollow noopener">Fionnuala</a> has called him, spends a lot of time labouring up and down steep hills in the sweltering heat. Even that seems to reflect his reluctant, difficult steps along the path he must take in the face of barbarism, ignorance and repression. He takes them, and then they get bigger.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12311507323714840624" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


