<div id="review_2850403803" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2850403803" />
    <a title="Susan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5837456-susan"><img alt="Susan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1372225128p2/5837456.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2850403803?book_show_action=true">Jul 09, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Susan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Susan" href="/user/show/5837456-susan">Susan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Audible Audio " href="/book/show/30739950-pereira-maintains">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2850403803" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1580567393590040484">I listened to this short novel on Audible, read by Derek Jacobi, whose voice was perfect for the slightly pompous, Dr Pereira. It is 1938 and Dr Pereira is a journalist at a time where politics could hardly be ignored. Yet, Dr Pereira maintains that he has no interest in such things – he loftily distains such views, as he is the editor of the culture page. <br/><br/>So far, his work has been conservative, rather than extreme. However, we get hints that others believe he should be saying more, including th</span>
  <span id="freeText1580567393590040484" style="display:none">I listened to this short novel on Audible, read by Derek Jacobi, whose voice was perfect for the slightly pompous, Dr Pereira. It is 1938 and Dr Pereira is a journalist at a time where politics could hardly be ignored. Yet, Dr Pereira maintains that he has no interest in such things – he loftily distains such views, as he is the editor of the culture page. <br /><br />So far, his work has been conservative, rather than extreme. However, we get hints that others believe he should be saying more, including the waiter, Manuel, who exhorts him genially that he should know what is going on. However, it is his meeting with a young man that opens his political eyes. Part of his susceptibility to this young man is the fact that Pereira is overweight, widowed, and lonely. He chats to the photograph of his wife and dreams of the son they never had. In a way, Rossi, the young man he meets, becomes this son and Pereira gives him money and begins to feel responsible for him. <br /><br />This is wrapped up as a simple story, which has a great deal of depth. Pereira is a likeable soul, with his love for lemonade (half sugar…), omelettes and reminiscences of the past. Although this is a story of a political awakening, this is much humour and events that we can all sympathise with. Not only the larger things, such as Pereira’s regret at being childless, but the sarcastic attendant at the beach, who sneers at Dr Pereira’s weight or the newspaper Editor in Chief, who never really listens. A novel I am glad that I read. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1580567393590040484" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


