    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1503374841" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1503374841" />
    <a title="AdiTurbo" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2199883-aditurbo"><img alt="AdiTurbo" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1267856658p2/2199883.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1503374841?book_show_action=true">Jan 09, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="AdiTurbo" class="user" itemprop="url" name="AdiTurbo" href="/user/show/2199883-aditurbo">AdiTurbo</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9781847675712" href="/book/show/7849308-pereira-maintains">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1503374841" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17674635908941299348">This is one of the best books I have ever read, and now sits well on my favorites shelf. It is so subtly sophisticated and clever - you don&apos;t see much anymore of such superb writing. <br/>The story takes place while Fascist regimes are rising in the world in the 1930s. Our protagonist, Pereira, is a Portuguese man who has lost his beloved wife some time ago, but still talks to her through her picture every day. He works as the editor of a culture page in a Catholic magazine, and see himself as comple</span>
  <span id="freeText17674635908941299348" style="display:none">This is one of the best books I have ever read, and now sits well on my favorites shelf. It is so subtly sophisticated and clever - you don't see much anymore of such superb writing. <br />The story takes place while Fascist regimes are rising in the world in the 1930s. Our protagonist, Pereira, is a Portuguese man who has lost his beloved wife some time ago, but still talks to her through her picture every day. He works as the editor of a culture page in a Catholic magazine, and see himself as completely separate from what is happening al around him, and as "non-political". But of course, there is no such thing as "non-political", especially when your country begins to lose its moral ground, as I should well know, living in such a country right now. You can't stay uninvolved. It simply isn't possible. Things get to you some way or another, touch your life, your conscience, your soul. And indeed, things happen in Pereira's life and in his soul that make him have to change his stance. This process is described so delicately, beautifully and accurately, that you know the writer has had to have gone through it himself. Everyone who has lived through Fascism knows that the slippery slope has you experience tiny change after tiny change, but soon enough, everything is different. Even more brilliant is the use of the word "maintains". I have never seen such a brilliant use of just one word in any novel. The word points to only one possibility - that the narrator must belong to some kind of authority, and is reporting the story to someone else as the evidence of a witness or suspect. This makes the reader feel exactly what Pereira is feeling - an omenous and dark sense of threat over everything that takes place. <br />What a fantastic read! I will never forget this book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17674635908941299348" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


